@node sect3 "Description"
Samtools is a public domain collection of programs to allow Sun systems to read and write files on a SAMDOS diskette in the floppy disk drive /dev/rfd0.  Alternatively, these programs may be used to manipulate an image of a SAMDOS diskette which is stored in a file, for example for the use of the XCoupe emulator. SAMDOS filenames are composed of ten characters each.  Any ASCII character is allowed, including spaces, but the use of spaces or wildcards will require the names to be quoted to protect them from the shell. 

The "pattern matching" routines follow the Unix-style rules, using "*" for "zero or more characters" and "?" for "precisely one character".  The Unix-style "[]" is not supported.  The read-only attribute bit is ignored during pattern matching.  Upper and lower case letters are considered equivalent, as they are in SamDOS. 

Some support is provided for MasterDOS disks.  If a disk has a name then it will be printed out by @{b}samdir@{ub}, and any extra MasterDOS directory tracks will be taken into account. Some programs support MasterDOS directories.  If the environment variable SAMDIR is set then this is the name of the current directory; otherwise the root directory is current.  In some cases the name of a file may contain leading directory names which are separated by the current delimiter, which is normally '/' but can be changed by setting the environment variable SAMSEPARATOR.  If the name begins with this character then the name is relative to the root directory; otherwise it is relative to the current directory.  If the disk being used is in SAMDOS format then filenames are not checked for leading directory names. 

If the SAMDISKFILE environment variable is set, it holds the name of a disk image that samtools will use instead of the real floppy disk device. The file must exist and be at least (preferably exactly) 819200 bytes in length.  The name of a disk image may also be supplied using the @{b}-diskfile @{ub}@{i}file@{ui} flag after the command name. 


@endnode

@node sect4 "Environment"


· SAMDIR @{lindent 3}
The name of the current directory. @{lindent 0}

· SAMDISKFILE @{lindent 3}
The name of a disk image file. A disk image file may be created simply by writing a file of all zeros. The command @{lindent 0}

· @{b}samdiskread -disk /dev/zero@{ub} @{lindent 3}
@{i}newdiskname@{ui} @{lindent 0}

· or@{lindent 3}
samformat -disk @{i}newdiskname@{ui} @{lindent 0}

· will do this.  The disk may be labelled using @{lindent 3}
@{i}samlabel@{ui}. @{lindent 0}

· SAMSEPARATOR @{lindent 3}
The character which separates directory components of MasterDOS file names (note: Unix file names always use a slash character). @{lindent 0}


@endnode

